{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1882303d-746d-4601-abbc-0a40ba6b9d6b","content":"No worries — here's how to configure `.vscode/mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport:\n\n```jsonc\n// .vscode/mcp.json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Place the file at **`.vscode/mcp.json`** in your workspace root.\n- `type: \"stdio\"` means Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- Your server must read JSON-RPC messages from stdin and write responses to stdout (the `Microsoft.Extensions.AI` or `ModelContextProtocol` SDK handles this).\n- **Don't** write logs to stdout — use stderr instead, or they'll corrupt the protocol.\n\nIf you've already published/built the server, you can point directly at the DLL for faster startup:\n\n```jsonc\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"exec\", \"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Debug/net8.0/MyMcpServer.dll\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2490af9a-89d0-44ab-8cbd-1f1e0630247d","outputTokens":343,"requestId":"F419:6E901:1B7CB9D:1E4B053:69FDA8C5"},"id":"70b3c509-51de-40ec-b629-40d864fc7eb4","timestamp":"2026-05-08T09:11:43.635Z","parentId":"b2be12af-e33a-4a09-893b-09d4aee06735"}
